"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833752","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-02-02","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to the statement made by myself, <a href="https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2018-01-30/debates/F35E85CB-FF67-467E-AD63-1C13EB1EC32B/PIPBackPayments" target="_blank">Official Report</a>, 30 January 2018, Column 703.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-02-02T14:54:30.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833752/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833752/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833752/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-30","Personal Independence Payment: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 29 January 2018 to Question 124308, on Personal Independence Payment: Mental Health, if her Department will compensate personal independence payment claimants who are entitled to a back payment and have fallen into debt and accrued interest.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","125510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833753","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-08","<p>Following the transfer of staff from Carillion, Gov Facility Services Limited will employ circa 900 staff.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2018-02-08T13:52:42.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833753/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833753/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833753/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-30","Gov Facility Services: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many staff are employed by Gov Facility Services Limited.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","125511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833754","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-08","<p>When Gov Facility Services Limited becomes operational its immediate priority is to maintain the delivery of facilities management services to prisons. It is too early to determine the precise plans to privatise or contract out any of the work of Gov Facility Services Limited or advise on any future recruitment plans.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2018-02-08T13:53:07.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833754/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833754/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833754/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-30","Gov Facility Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether the Government has plans to privatise or contract out any of the work of Gov Facility Services Limited.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","125512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833755","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-09","<p>The estimated costs of running Gov Facility Services Limited, excluding sub-contractor costs, for financial years 2018/19, FY2019/20 and FY2020/21 is £160,000,000. This option was chosen as it was the best option for tax payers as well as ensuring continuity of service.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2018-02-09T12:36:53.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833755/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833755/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833755/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-30","Gov Facility Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate his Department has made of the cost to the public purse of running the company Gov Facility Services Limited in each year from 2018 to 2022.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","125513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833756","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-08","<p>The services agreement with Gov Facility Services Limited will be overseen by members of Her Majesty’s Prison and Probation Service (HMPPS) National Service Management Team. The team consists of 97 staff Full Time Equivalent (FTE) and are responsible for monitoring the delivery of contracts for all outsourced prison maintenance by private sector companies.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2018-02-08T13:54:39.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833756/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833756/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833756/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-30","Gov Facility Services: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many staff of his Department are responsible for managing Gov Facility Services Limited.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","125514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833757","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-01","<p>In addition to the staff that were transferred to that company from Carillion it is anticipated that Gov Facility Services Limited will be required to recruit staff once the company becomes operational to ensure the smooth transfer and continuity of service.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-03-01T18:28:17.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833757/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833757/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833757/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-30","Gov Facility Services: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether his Department has plans to recruit staff to work for Gov Facility Services Limited in addition to the staff that were transferred to that company from Carillion.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","125515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833758","HM Treasury","false","2018-02-05","<p>Ministers and officials from my department have regular discussions with our counterparts in MHCLG to discuss a range of issues, including housing and planning.</p><p> </p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-02-05T12:01:35.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833758/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833758/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833758/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-30","Compulsory Purchase","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government on implementing (a) clauses 195 and 196 of the Housing and Planning Act 2016 and (b) clauses 38 and 39 of the Neighbourhood Planning Act 2017.","false","Biography information for Robert Neill","Bromley and Chislehurst","Robert Neill","125516"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833759","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-06","<p>Except with reference to the Written Answer by Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth on 1 November 2017 (HL2050), the Government is fully committed to implementing all measures across both the Housing and Planning Act 2016 and the Neighbourhood Planning Act 2017.</p><p>We are taking end-to-end action to fix our broken housing market through our wider package of reforms, including last year’s Housing White Paper and the measures announced at Autumn Budget. We regularly update the House on progress towards fixing our broken housing market, and will continue to do so.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-02-06T16:08:05.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833759/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833759/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833759/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-30","Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, if he will publish a timetable for implementing the measures yet to be commenced in the (a) Housing and Planning Act 2016 and (b) Neighbourhood Planning Act 2017.","false","Biography information for Robert Neill","Bromley and Chislehurst","Robert Neill","125517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833760","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-06","<p>Details of Ministers' meetings with external organisations are published quarterly on Gov.uk and can be found at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dclg-ministerial-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dclg-ministerial-data</a></p><p>Since May 2017 departmental officials have met with Transport for London, Homes England, Scottish Government, the Country Land and Business Association, the Compulsory Purchase Association, Shelter and the National Infrastructure Commission to discuss general compulsory purchase matters.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-02-06T16:05:59.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833760/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833760/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833760/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-30","Compulsory Purchase","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, if he will publish a list of meetings (a) he and (b) officials of his Department have had with organisations outside of his Department on the matter of compulsory purchase since 1 May 2017.","false","Biography information for Robert Neill","Bromley and Chislehurst","Robert Neill","125518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833761","HM Treasury","false","2018-02-07","<p>HM Treasury is currently carrying out its review into the Isle of Man’s administration of VAT in relation to aircraft and yachts. HM Treasury aims to complete the review in Spring 2018.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-02-07T15:37:20.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833761/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833761/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833761/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-30","Aircraft: Isle of Man","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when the scoping assessment of his Department's review of the taxation of the import of business jets into the Isle of Man will be published.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Dame Margaret Hodge","125519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833762","HM Treasury","false","2018-02-07","<p>HM Treasury is currently carrying out a review of the Isle of Man’s VAT procedures for the importation of aircraft and yachts. We will maintain regular contact with the Commission as the review progresses.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-02-07T15:39:19.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833762/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833762/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833762/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-30","Aircraft: Isle of Man","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what correspondence he has had with Pierre Moscovici on the import of business jets to the Isle of Man.","false","Biography information for Dame Margaret Hodge","Barking","Dame Margaret Hodge","125520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833763","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-05","<p>Data on admissions to custody following sentence, covering 2010 to 2016, is published online and can be found in table 2.6 in the following link.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/610978/receptions-2016.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/610978/receptions-2016.xlsx</a></p><p> </p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-02-05T09:40:46.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833763/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833763/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833763/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-30","Prison Sentences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people were sentenced to custodial sentences in (a) men's and (b) women's prisons in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","125521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833764","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-02","<p>We are unable to provide a breakdown as requested for those who have served in the armed forces. The Ministry began collecting data on service in the armed forces from 2015. All newly received offenders into custody (convicted or remanded) are now asked on reception if they have served in the armed forces. Latest figures published in October 2017 show approximately 3% of offenders who responded to the question were former members of the armed forces. This has been a similar level to the previous four quarters. Due to the very small number of female ex-armed service personnel in prisons this number is not split by gender.</p><p> </p><p>Prisoners who choose to identify as veterans are given access to available specialist support via the armed forces. This includes support for issues such as post traumatic stress disorder (PTSD), that may affect them following their service. Additional support can be offered by military service charities working with prisons and rehabilitation services.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-02-02T14:46:38.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833764/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833764/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833764/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-30","Sentencing: Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people who were currently serving or had previously served in HM Armed Forces were sentenced to custodial sentences in (a) men's and (b) women's prisons in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","125522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833765","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-02-07","<p>We have no plans to reduce the legal protection afforded to badgers in England.</p><p> </p><p>The Devon and Cornwall Constabulary have never advocated the removal of the Protection of Badgers Act across the UK.</p><p> </p><p>In responding to a consultation in 2015 about the criteria for badger control (culling) licences, they suggested an option might be for Defra to consider the removal of the Act in cull zones to allow greater flexibility in the methods used to stop the spread of Bovine TB. Defra did not consider this necessary.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-02-07T15:20:27.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833765/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833765/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833765/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-30","Badgers: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether he plans to hold discussions with the Devon and Cornwall Constabulary on its proposal to end the protection of badgers.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","125523"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833766","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-02","<p>We have assumed that the hon. Member is referring to Complex Regional Pain Syndrome. Data outlining how many people have been diagnosed with this condition is not available.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-02-02T14:35:36.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833766/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833766/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833766/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-30","Complex Regional Pain Syndrome","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many people have been diagnosed with Chronic Regional Pain Syndrome aged (a) under 18, (b) between 18 and 25, (c) between 46 and 64 and (d) 65 and over in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Ruth George","High Peak","Ruth George","125524"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833767","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-02-05","<p>The contaminated blood scandal was an appalling tragedy that should never have happened. The Inquiry is a priority for Government. The Inquiry and its Chair, once appointed, will want to engage with victims all over the UK. The Parliamentary Secretary has confirmed that she will write to you directly about how Government will consult the Northern Ireland Executive and Civil Service under the Inquiries Act 2005.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2018-02-05T16:48:00.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833767/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833767/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833767/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-01-30","Blood: Contamination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what recent discussions she has had with the Minister for the Cabinet Office on the inquiry into contaminated blood under the Inquiries Act 2005.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","125525"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833768","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-02-02","<p>In the absence of an Executive it has fallen to the Northern Ireland Civil Service to protect and preserve public services in Northern Ireland. The Secretary of State would like to put on record again her gratitude to David Sterling, as Head of the Northern Ireland Civil Service, and all of his colleagues, for the professionalism they have shown in taking on that responsibility.</p><p> </p><p>We want to see a restored Executive taking forward the 2018-19 Budget, with the difficult decisions it requires made by locally elected politicians in the interests of the whole community. That will remain our overriding priority. In the meantime, the Secretary of State liaises regularly with David Sterling on a range of issues concerning the maintenance of public services, including the Budget situation, and that engagement will continue in the important weeks ahead.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2018-02-02T10:33:53.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833768/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833768/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833768/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-01-30","Public Expenditure: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what recent discussions she has had with the head of the Northern Ireland civil service about the budget for the next financial year; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","125526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833769","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-02-06","<p>Secretary of State and I met with Invest NI last month to discuss trade and investment in Northern Ireland. We recognise the great potential of Northern Ireland and Ministers in the Northern Ireland Office will continue to use every possible opportunity alongside colleagues from across Government to work closely with Invest NI to promote Northern Ireland as a great place to invest and do business.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2018-02-06T14:44:05.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833769/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833769/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833769/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-01-30","Trade: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what recent discussions she has had with Invest NI about trade and investment in Northern Ireland; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Nigel Dodds","125527"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833770","Department for Transport","false","2018-02-05","<p>All vehicles must meet strict emission standards before they enter use and emissions from private cars are then checked at the annual MoT for cars of 3 years age and older.</p><p> </p><p>Smoky lorries and buses can be reported by telephone via DVSA’s national number, online via GOV.UK or by sending an email. DVSA will then send a letter to the registered keeper of the vehicle as recorded on the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency’s database. The letter is also copied to the remote enforcement office at DVSA. The operator is then required to undergo an emissions test and submit the results to DVSA’s enforcement team.</p><p> </p><p>The Government currently has no plans to extend the ability to report suspected excessive lorry and bus exhaust emissions to private cars and motorcycles. It remains the user’s responsibility to ensure the vehicle continues to meet these emissions standards at all times while in use.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-02-05T14:03:12.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833770/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833770/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833770/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-30","Motor Vehicles: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he plans to extend the ability to report excessive emissions at present applied to buses and commercial vehicles to private cars and motorcycles; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","125528"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833771","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-02-02","<p>The Government does not comment on leaks or ongoing leak enquiries. The document to which the question refers represents preliminary analysis and has only very recently been presented to ministers. It does not reflect this Government’s policy, and is not representative of the expected outcome of the negotiations. Ministers have a duty not to publish anything that could risk exposing our negotiation position.</p><p><strong><br></strong>The Government has agreed to make this analysis available to the EU Exit Select Committee and to all members of both Houses through a confidential reading room, once arrangements can be made.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","125530 ; 125531","2018-02-02T14:48:02.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833771/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833771/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833771/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-01-30","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, for what reasons the document EU Exit Analysis – Cross Whitehall Briefing was seen by journalists before hon. Members were given access to it.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","125529"
