124093, on Social Security Benefits: Appeals, how many people waited (a) less than one month, (b) less than two months, (c) less than three months, (d) less than four months, (e) less than five months, (f) less than six months and (g) six months or more for mandatory reconsideration for universal credit in each year since its introduction.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","125534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833777","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-02","<p>The Government has set aside £5m to celebrate this milestone in British democracy.</p><p> </p><p>In the Autumn budget, the Chancellor announced that £1.2million of the centenary fund would go directly to seven centenary cities and towns in England with a strong suffrage history, to strengthen the reach and legacy of regional activity to inspire a new generation with this story.</p><p> </p><p>A further £1.5million will be available to organisations and communities through a grants scheme. Online applications opened in January, and further information can be found at: www.womensvotecentenaryfund.co.uk</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Justice is dedicated to achieving gender equality both in the workplace and in our justice system. The department’s Gender Equality Forum is organising a series of events to celebrate and commemorate the centenary of women’s suffrage as well as International Women’s Day on the 8<sup>th</sup> March.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-02-02T14:15:46.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833777/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833777/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833777/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-30","Voting Rights: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether his Department plans to mark the centenary of the first women getting the right to vote in 1918.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","125535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833778","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-07","<p>The Government remains committed to undertaking a post-implementation review on the impact of the changes brought about by LASPO and publishing it later this year.</p><p>The post-implementation review is an evidence-based assessment of changes brought about by LASPO; this involves analysing evidence and consulting with expert panels and interested parties.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-02-07T14:01:35.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833778/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833778/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833778/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-30","Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what progress his Department has made on the post-implementation review of the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","125536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833779","HM Treasury","false","2018-02-02","<p>There are plans to have an internal event organised by HMT staff to mark 100 years since some women were given the right to vote in the UK.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2018-02-02T08:59:31.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833779/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833779/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833779/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-30","Voting Rights: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department plans to mark the centenary of women getting the right to vote in 1918.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","125537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833780","Home Office","false","2018-02-02","<p>The government has set aside £5m to celebrate this milestone in British democracy. Goverment wants to ensure that we support a range of organisations and communities to get involved.</p><p>£1.5million will be available to organisations and communities through a grants scheme. Further information can be found at: <a href="http://www.womensvotecentenaryfund.co.uk" target="_blank">www.womensvotecentenaryfund.co.uk</a></p><p>In the Autumn budget, the Chancellor announced that £1.2million of the centenary fund would go directly to seven Centenary Cities and towns in England with a strong suffrage history, to strengthen the reach and legacy of regional activity to inspire a new generation with this story.</p><p>My Officials in the Government Equalities Office are developing an exciting national programme to celebrate and remember the suffrage movement. This includes funding the statue of Millicent Fawcett in Parliament Square, and a suite of education programmes in partnership with the Department for Education and the Cabinet Office.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-02-02T13:12:16.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833780/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833780/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833780/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-30","Voting Rights: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department plans to mark the centenary of women getting the right to vote in 1918.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","125538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833781","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-02-02","<p>This year marks the centenary of British women securing the right to vote. We should not forget what it took to achieve that. The government has set aside £5m to celebrate this important milestone in our democracy. Events are being planned across government to honour the extraordinary sacrifices made by the many suffragettes and the landmark changes they brought about.</p><p><strong><br></strong>The Department for Exiting the European Union’s staff networks are planning a number of events and activities to mark the centenary. These include celebrating International Women's day and participating in a wider civil service event bringing together former, current and future leaders to discuss the important contributions women have made, and continue to make, in the civil service.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2018-02-02T14:50:45.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833781/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833781/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833781/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-01-30","Voting Rights: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether his Department plans to mark the centenary of women getting the right to vote in 1918.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","125539"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833782","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-02","<p>The Ministry of Defence plans to participate in the nationwide Suffrage Flag Relay, organised by the Cross-Government Women's Network as part of the Civil Service celebrations for the suffrage centenary. A number of Defence sites will host the flag at various points in 2018. We will also promote the centenary of women's suffrage across our sites to raise awareness and encourage celebratory activities throughout the year.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-02-02T14:26:38.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833782/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833782/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833782/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-30","Voting Rights: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department plans to mark the centenary of women getting the right to vote in 1918.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","125540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833783","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-05","<p>Government will be consulting shortly on reforms to the Energy Company Obligation which will run from October 2018 to March 2022. The consultation will include proposals for supporting rural properties and the types of measures eligible. The Renewable Heat Incentive is targeted at off grid buildings using high carbon fuels, with a £4.5bn budget between 2016 and 2021.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-02-05T14:50:18.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833783/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833783/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833783/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-30","Fuel Oil: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will withdraw support from oil-heated properties where that property is off the gas grid and fuel inefficient.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","125541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833784","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-05","<p>Using the gas grid to transport hydrogen is one of a number of potential approaches to decarbonise how we heat our homes, businesses and industry in order to meet our 2050 emissions reduction targets. As outlined in the Clean Growth Strategy, approaches with potential include decarbonising the gas grid using hydrogen or biogas, increased use of heat networks and electrification of heating. At present, it is not clear which approaches will work best at scale. The Department is carrying out work to consolidate and improve the evidence base on different approaches and plans to publish a report on this work in summer 2018.</p><p>Last year, the Department commenced a £25m innovation project to explore the potential use of hydrogen in UK homes and businesses, including through development and testing of hydrogen appliances. Also last year, Ofgem awarded £8.9m to the gas distribution networks, under the Network Innovation Competition, to provide evidence on the suitability and safety of using existing distribution infrastructure to transport hydrogen.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-02-05T14:49:07.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833784/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833784/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833784/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-30","Hydrogen: National Grid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the merits of using the current gas grid to transport hydrogen.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","125542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833785","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-05","<p>The below table gives estimates of the proportion of homes not attached to the gas grid by Government Office Region as of 31 December 2016, which are the most recent estimates available. The estimates are based on the difference between the number of households and the number of domestic gas meters as published in the sub-national gas consumption data. Further details of the methodology, and additional data are published at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/sub-national-estimates-of-households-not-connected-to-the-gas-network" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/sub-national-estimates-of-households-not-connected-to-the-gas-network</a></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Great Britain`</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>14%</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>13%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North East</p></td><td><p>6%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North West</p></td><td><p>7%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Yorkshire and The Humber</p></td><td><p>8%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East Midlands</p></td><td><p>10%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>West Midlands</p></td><td><p>11%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East</p></td><td><p>18%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Inner London</p></td><td><p>20%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Outer London</p></td><td><p>12%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South East</p></td><td><p>14%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South West</p></td><td><p>21%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wales</p></td><td><p>17%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Scotland</p></td><td><p>20%</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-02-05T15:26:00.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833785/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833785/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833785/answer","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833785/answer/previousversion/39106","Biography information for Claire Perry","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-30","Natural Gas: National Grid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what proportion of homes are not currently attached to the gas grid by region.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","125543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833786","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-02-02","<p>The UK is playing a leading role in diplomatic efforts, including bringing together key international actors to try to find a peaceful solution to the conflict in Yemen. As part of this we proposed the Presidential Statement passed at the UN Security Council in June this year, which called for an end to the fighting and a return to UN-led peace talks. We are now working urgently with our international and regional partners to ensure that the Security Council's words are converted into action. We call on all parties to respect these unified and clear demands from the international community. More recently, the Foreign Secretary hosted a meeting of his US, Saudi and Emirati counterparts in our Embassy in Paris on 23 January. They discussed ways of addressing the humanitarian crisis in Yemen, countering weapons smuggling and refocusing the political track to move towards a peaceful solution to the conflict.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-02-02T14:37:56.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833786/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833786/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833786/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-30","Yemen: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent steps his Department has taken to progress the peace talks between parties to conflict in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","125544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833787","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-02-02","<p>We continue to engage with the Saudi-led Coalition on its Yemen Comprehensive Humanitarian Operations Plan (YCHOP). Improving humanitarian access to all of Yemen is key to alleviating the crisis. Continued access for commercial supplies, including food and fuel through the ports of Hodeidah and Saleef, is critical to ensuring that the Yemeni people get the supplies they so desperately need. The Coalition has publicly stated that corridor originating points will include Al Khadara, Al Tuwal, Hodeidah, Mokha, Aden and Marib.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-02-02T14:14:30.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833787/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833787/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833787/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-30","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what information his Department has received from the Saudi-led Coalition on the location and inspection system of the 17 safe-passage corridors from 6 points of entry announced on 22 January 2018.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","125545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833788","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-02-02","<p>The Government is aware of the predicament facing producers of goat’s milk following the decision by two processors to give notice of contract termination to at least some of their suppliers. Whilst this is fundamentally a commercial matter to which producers and processors are best placed to develop a sustainable solution, we welcome the recent statement from the Milking Goats Association encouraging goats’ milk producers to engage closely with their processors, and to establish export relationships and new markets.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-02-02T12:53:01.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833788/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833788/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833788/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-30","Goats: Milk","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what support his Department plans to provide to goat farmers affected by the loss of contracts as a result the oversupply of goat's milk.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Sir Mark Hendrick","125546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833789","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-05","<p>The impact assessment on the Nuclear Safeguards Bill, prepared by the Department of Business Energy and Industrial Strategy, was submitted to the Regulatory Policy Committee for approval on Tuesday 3<sup>rd</sup> October 2017.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2018-02-05T10:47:08.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833789/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833789/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833789/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-30","Nuclear Safeguards Bill 2017-19","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, on what date was the original impact assessment prepared by his Department for the Nuclear Safeguards Bill was submitted to the Regulatory Policy Committee for approval.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","125547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833790","Home Office","false","2018-02-02","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to the answer given to the Hon. Member for Weaver Vale on 15 January 2018, UIN 121711.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-02-02T11:02:47.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833790/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833790/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833790/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-30","Hunting Act 2004: Cheshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she has made an assessment of the level of enforcement of the Hunting Act 2004 in Cheshire; and if she will make an statement.","false","Biography information for Laura Smith","Crewe and Nantwich","Laura Smith","125548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833791","HM Treasury","false","2018-02-02","<p>The Government’s shareholding in the Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS) is managed at arm's length and on a commercial basis through UK Financial Investments Ltd, a company which is wholly owned by the Government.</p><p> </p><p>RBS has made significant progress on resolving its legacy issues and refocusing on serving British businesses and consumers. The Government’s policy remains to return its shareholding in RBS to the private sector, when it represents value for money to do so and market conditions allow. At Autumn Budget 2017, the Government announced that it intends to recommence RBS share sales before the end of 2018‑19, and dispose of around £15 billion worth of shares by 2023.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-02-02T11:41:16.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833791/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833791/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833791/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-30","Royal Bank of Scotland: Government Shareholding","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect on the Government's shareholding in RBS of changes in the level of RBS customers.","false","Biography information for Danielle Rowley","Midlothian","Danielle Rowley","125549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833792","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-02-02","<p>The total that DWP has spent on Universal Credit complaints is included in high level support costs, such as management and corporate overheads. These costs cannot be split out from overall Departmental spending on benefit payments and, therefore, an amount spent on complaints is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-02-02T09:47:23.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833792/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833792/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833792/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-30","Universal Credit: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much the Department has spent on processing complaints relating to universal credit.","false","Biography information for Danielle Rowley","Midlothian","Danielle Rowley","125550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833793","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-07","<p>In April 2012, my Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State announced that £250 million will be invested to build proton beam therapy facilities at The Christie Hospital in Manchester and University College London Hospitals in London. Building work is well underway on both sites and service planning and development is on schedule to begin treating patients from August 2018 at The Christie and summer 2020 for University College London Hospitals.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-02-07T13:59:24.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833793/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833793/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833793/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-30","Radiotherapy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what plans he has to widen access to proton radiotherapy for cancer patients in England.","false","Biography information for Julia Lopez","Hornchurch and Upminster","Julia Lopez","125551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833794","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-02-02","<p>The Department carries out a range of activities to check that sites in all constituencies are well prepared and ready for the local rollout of Universal Credit.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-02-02T11:46:49.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833794/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833794/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833794/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-30","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether assessments are being carried out at the constituency level on the roll-out of universal credit.","false","Biography information for Danielle Rowley","Midlothian","Danielle Rowley","125552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833795","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-07","<p>Being in hospital can be traumatic for any patient, but especially so for children. Providing a warm and caring environment, including access to television services, is therefore very important and National Health Service trusts are expected to provide this as a matter of course. Data for 2017 shows that 93% of organisations provide children in hospitals with a range of equipment appropriate to their age, including a bedside TV, radio and telephone.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Digital is working to make sure that everyone can access free WiFi in NHS sites in England. NHS WiFi will provide a secure, stable, and reliable WiFi capability, consistent across all NHS settings. It will allow patients and the public to download health apps, browse the internet and access health and care information.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-02-07T14:12:49.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833795/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833795/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833795/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-30","Hospital Wards: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether he has plans to ensure that NHS England provides (a) complementary wifi and (b) basic television services in children's hospital wards.","false","Biography information for Julia Lopez","Hornchurch and Upminster","Julia Lopez","125553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833796","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-07","<p>The Department promotes active public involvement in research into all conditions, including cancer. The Department does this through its funding of the National Institute of Health Research (NIHR) INVOLVE organisation, which aims to support active public involvement in National Health Service, public health and social care research.</p><p> </p><p>Underlining the Department’s commitment to the fight against cancer, NIHR funding for cancer research has risen from £101 million in 2010/11 to £137 million in 2016/17.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-02-07T12:19:40.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833796/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833796/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833796/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-30","Cancer: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether he has plans to promote volunteering in IBM's World Community Grid to support research into childhood cancers.","false","Biography information for Julia Lopez","Hornchurch and Upminster","Julia Lopez","125554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833797","Department for Education","false","2018-02-07","<p>The government recognises the value of physical activity for pupils. Schools have the freedom to decide which programmes they wish to adopt to suit their pupils.</p><p> </p><p>Active Movement Limited is a private company and the department has not made any assessment of the programme on exam achievement levels.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-02-07T17:43:10.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833797/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833797/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833797/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-30","Pupils: Exercise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of the effect of the Active Movement programme on exam results in participating schools.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","125555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833798","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-07","<p>No assessment of the Active Movement programme has been made centrally. Physical activity and sport have an important role in maintaining and improving the health and wellbeing of children and young people, irrespective of their weight. They are a key part of the Government’s childhood obesity plan.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-02-07T13:51:56.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833798/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833798/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833798/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-30","Obesity: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made on the effect of the Active Movement programme on levels of childhood obesity.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","125556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833799","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-02-06","<p>The cross-Government sport strategy, Sporting Future, set out how important it is for all children to be healthy and active. The Active Movement programme aims to combat sedentary behaviour, and we would be happy to meet them to discuss effective ways to encourage children and young people to enjoy active lifestyles.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-02-06T12:35:12.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833799/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833799/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833799/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-30","Exercise: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the effect of the Active Movement programme on activity levels amongst children.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","125557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833800","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-07","<p>The United Kingdom National Screening Committee (UK NSC) last reviewed the evidence to screen for neuroblastoma in 2015 and recommended that screening should not be offered. This is because the evidence published at the time of the review was insufficient in terms of quality and volume to accurately answer key questions to introduce screening which included no evidence that a screening test that would only detect cases of neuroblastoma that needed treatment; and no evidence that neuroblastoma screening (at any age) would reduce the number of deaths from neuroblastoma.</p><p> </p><p>The UK NSC is due to review the evidence for neuroblastoma in 2019.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-02-07T13:54:59.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833800/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833800/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833800/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-30","Neuroblastoma: Babies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what analysis his Department has undertaken of the (a) cost and (b) effectiveness of mandatory testing of babies at birth for neuroblastoma.","false","Biography information for Julia Lopez","Hornchurch and Upminster","Julia Lopez","125558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833801","Home Office","false","2018-02-06","<p>In most instances, a single caseworker will consider an individual’s application and correspond with that applicant as appropriate in order to make a decision. However, on occasion an application may be considered by a different caseworker, for example due to absence. In addition, and to provide excellent customer service, the department has correspondence teams who can respond to case specific enquiries from applicants, and MP account manager teams who can provide a similar service for members. This aids in the effective operation and efficiency of the department.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-02-06T14:12:10.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833801/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833801/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833801/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-30","Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 29 January 2018 to Question 124494, what assessment she has made of the effect of removing the named worker system on the effectiveness and efficiency of the immigration application system.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","125559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833802","Home Office","false","2018-02-06","<p>The Tier 1 (Exceptional Talent) route demonstrates our commitment to continuing to attract top international talent in the digital technology, science and arts sectors. On 11 January we doubled the number of places available to applicants from 1000, to 2000, and are confident that this is sufficient to meet demand at this time. We will continue to monitor take up of the route.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-02-06T16:33:21.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833802/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833802/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833802/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-01-30","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent assessment she has made of the adequacy of the availability of Tier 1 (Exceptional Talent) Visas.","false","Biography information for Adam Afriyie","Windsor","Adam Afriyie","125560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833803","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-02","<p>The total number of physical restrictive interventions collected in the Mental Health Services Data Set in 2016/17 is 53,188. This figure is taken from the first publication of annual figures on the use of restrictive interventions in inpatient mental health, learning disabilities and autism services.</p><p> </p><p>This is the first publication of this data and there are potential issues about which NHS Digital is making further assessment of the quality and completeness of these experimental statistics following this publication.</p><p> </p><p>Data on the inappropriate use of restraint is not collected.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-02-02T11:51:01.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833803/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833803/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833803/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-30","Mental Health Services: Restraint Techniques","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many instances of physical restraint were recorded on the Mental Health Services Data Set in each of the last years; and how many of those instances were recorded as an inappropriate use of physical restraint.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","125561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833804","HM Treasury","false","2018-02-07","<p>Fintech offers a significant opportunity for the financial sector, providing new jobs and delivering benefits to consumers through increased competition and innovation. It contributes £6.6bn annually to the UK economy, employing 60,000 people across 1,600 companies.</p><p> </p><p>The most recent step taken to promote the UK’s fintech industry, is the government’s second International Fintech Conference, due to be held on 22 March 2018. The conference will help showcase the UK fintech sector to investors from across the globe.</p><p> </p><p>The government is continuing to support alternative finance, through implementing proportionate, principles based regimes for peer-to-peer (P2P) and equity-based crowdfunding that balance consumer protection with allowing the sectors to grow and evolve; and various supportive tax measures.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","125567 ; 125568","2018-02-07T12:24:05.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833804/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833804/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833804/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-30","Financial Services: Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent steps he has taken to promote financial technology.","false","Biography information for Adam Afriyie","Windsor","Adam Afriyie","125562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833805","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-07","<p>In January 2017 the Department launched a consultation on proposals to fix/limit the costs recoverable by claimant lawyers in lower value clinical negligence cases. The Department published a holding response to the consultation on 25 July 2017, so as to allow the Department time to reflect the recommendations made by the Right Honourable Lord Justice Jackson following his review in to fixed costs, published on 31 July.</p><p> </p><p>Lord Justice Jackson’s report includes a recommendation for the Civil Justice Council (CJC) and the Government to set up a working party to develop a new process for clinical negligence initially up to £25,000 alongside a new fixed costs regime.</p><p> </p><p>Departmental ministers have agreed with this recommendation, as referenced in the recent Public Accounts Committee 29 November 2017, and the Department is now preparing the final response to the consultation for publication. The publication dates will be decided according to standard Government processes.</p><p> </p><p>The CJC are independent of the Department and will publish details of the working party as recommended by Lord Justice Jackson in due course.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","125566","2018-02-07T13:47:52.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833805/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833805/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833805/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-30","NHS: Negligence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, when he plans to publish the outcome of the consultation on fixed recoverable costs for clinical negligence claims.","false","Biography information for Craig Tracey","North Warwickshire","Craig Tracey","125563"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833806","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-02","<p>Current Departmental guidance (‘Positive and Proactive Care: reducing the need for restrictive interventions’, April 2014) states that organisations that provide care and support to people who are at risk of being exposed to restrictive interventions must have clear organisational policies which reflect professional or clinical guidance, current legislation, case law and evidence of best practice.</p><p> </p><p>Providers must ensure that these policies are available and accessible to users of services and carers.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-02-02T11:55:34.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833806/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833806/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833806/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-30","Mental Health Services: Restraint Techniques","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if he will require all healthcare trusts to publish their restraint policies.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","125564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833807","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-02","<p>Incidents of restraint of children and young people in contact with Mental Health, Learning Disabilities or Autism Spectrum Disorder Services are already recorded by trusts in the Mental Health Services Dataset. This records the date of the intervention, and the type.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-02-02T11:58:47.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833807/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833807/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833807/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-30","Mental Health Services: Restraint Techniques","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if he will require healthcare trusts to record data on use of physical restraint on children.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","125565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833808","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-07","<p>In January 2017 the Department launched a consultation on proposals to fix/limit the costs recoverable by claimant lawyers in lower value clinical negligence cases. The Department published a holding response to the consultation on 25 July 2017, so as to allow the Department time to reflect the recommendations made by the Right Honourable Lord Justice Jackson following his review in to fixed costs, published on 31 July.</p><p> </p><p>Lord Justice Jackson’s report includes a recommendation for the Civil Justice Council (CJC) and the Government to set up a working party to develop a new process for clinical negligence initially up to £25,000 alongside a new fixed costs regime.</p><p> </p><p>Departmental ministers have agreed with this recommendation, as referenced in the recent Public Accounts Committee 29 November 2017, and the Department is now preparing the final response to the consultation for publication. The publication dates will be decided according to standard Government processes.</p><p> </p><p>The CJC are independent of the Department and will publish details of the working party as recommended by Lord Justice Jackson in due course.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","125563","2018-02-07T13:47:52.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833808/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833808/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833808/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-30","NHS: Negligence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, when he plans to respond to the Lord Justice Jackson review on fixed recoverable costs for clinical negligence claims.","false","Biography information for Craig Tracey","North Warwickshire","Craig Tracey","125566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833809","HM Treasury","false","2018-02-07","<p>Fintech offers a significant opportunity for the financial sector, providing new jobs and delivering benefits to consumers through increased competition and innovation. It contributes £6.6bn annually to the UK economy, employing 60,000 people across 1,600 companies.</p><p> </p><p>The most recent step taken to promote the UK’s fintech industry, is the government’s second International Fintech Conference, due to be held on 22 March 2018. The conference will help showcase the UK fintech sector to investors from across the globe.</p><p> </p><p>The government is continuing to support alternative finance, through implementing proportionate, principles based regimes for peer-to-peer (P2P) and equity-based crowdfunding that balance consumer protection with allowing the sectors to grow and evolve; and various supportive tax measures.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","125562 ; 125568","2018-02-07T12:24:05.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833809/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833809/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833809/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-30","Financial Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent steps he has taken to promote alternative finance.","false","Biography information for Adam Afriyie","Windsor","Adam Afriyie","125567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833810","HM Treasury","false","2018-02-07","<p>Fintech offers a significant opportunity for the financial sector, providing new jobs and delivering benefits to consumers through increased competition and innovation. It contributes £6.6bn annually to the UK economy, employing 60,000 people across 1,600 companies.</p><p> </p><p>The most recent step taken to promote the UK’s fintech industry, is the government’s second International Fintech Conference, due to be held on 22 March 2018. The conference will help showcase the UK fintech sector to investors from across the globe.</p><p> </p><p>The government is continuing to support alternative finance, through implementing proportionate, principles based regimes for peer-to-peer (P2P) and equity-based crowdfunding that balance consumer protection with allowing the sectors to grow and evolve; and various supportive tax measures.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen","125562 ; 125567","2018-02-07T12:24:05.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833810/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833810/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833810/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-30","Financial Services: Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment he has made of the contribution of financial technology to the UK’s financial sector.","false","Biography information for Adam Afriyie","Windsor","Adam Afriyie","125568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833811","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-07","<p>Our probation staff do a vital and challenging job reforming offenders and protecting the public.</p><p> </p><p>The National Probation Service (NPS) was created in June 2014 as part of the wider Probation Reforms. Prior to that date the Probation Service structure was based on 35 local Government Probation Trusts. Since becoming Civil Servants in June 2014, the NPS staff have been in receipt of annual contractual pay awards which align to Government Pay Policy and the 1% spending controls.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-02-07T16:04:24.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833811/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833811/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833811/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-30","National Probation Service for England and Wales: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the change in real term pay is for those employed in the National Probation Service since 2010.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","125569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833812","Department for Education","false","2018-02-07","<p>Schools are free to cover enterprise and entrepreneurship within their personal, social, health and economic education.</p><p>The Government’s careers strategy, published in December 2017, aims to give young people from all backgrounds the opportunity to learn from employers about work and the skills that are valued in the workplace: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/careers-strategy-making-the-most-of-everyones-skills-and-talents" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/careers-strategy-making-the-most-of-everyones-skills-and-talents</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Statutory guidance sets out further details about the ambition that every school should offer every young person at least seven encounters with employers, including those who are self-employed, during their education as part of a high quality careers programme: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/careers-guidance-provision-for-young-people-in-schools" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/careers-guidance-provision-for-young-people-in-schools</a>. The Careers &amp; Enterprise Company’s network of Enterprise Advisers will support the delivery of this ambition. Enterprise Advisers are senior business volunteers who help schools to work with local businesses.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-02-07T17:48:47.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833812/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833812/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833812/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-30","Business: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to increase entrepreneurship and business education in schools.","false","Biography information for Adam Afriyie","Windsor","Adam Afriyie","125570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833813","Cabinet Office","false","2018-02-05","<p>This information is not currently held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>BEIS have recently introduced a payment reporting system, which requires large businesses to report on their UK payment practices and performance. Businesses must report every six months on their payment performance starting with their first full financial year that starts on or after 6 April 2017:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/business-payment-practices-and-performance-reporting-requirements" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/business-payment-practices-and-performance-reporting-requirements</a></p><p> </p><p>We intend to take further steps to improve payment practices in government supply chains and we will be bringing forward proposals shortly.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-02-05T16:49:32.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833813/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833813/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833813/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-30","Contracts: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 24 January to Question 123892, if he will publish the payment performance data for each prime contractor for the period between April and October 2017 inclusive.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","125571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833814","Department for Education","false","2018-02-02","<p>The department does not collect data in this level of detail for the child or young person’s type of need.</p><p> </p><p>We collect annual data from schools and colleges on special educational needs (SEN) as part of the School Census. This data is published annually each January.</p><p> </p><p>Primary type of need is collected for those pupils with a statement of SEN or Education, Health and Care (EHC) plan. There are 12 categories of need, including physical disability. This is the highest level of detail that is collected.</p><p> </p><p>The latest figures are available in Table 8 of the National Tables on the department’s website at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/special-educational-needs-in-england-january-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/special-educational-needs-in-england-january-2017</a>.</p><p>Under the Children and Families Act 2014, local authorities are required to conduct statutory EHC needs assessments to determine whether children and young people in their area have special educational needs which require additional support or provision. Where a local authority deems that a statutory EHC plan should be issued, it is responsible for securing the special educational provision specified in the plan.</p><p>The department has provided local authorities with £252 million between 2014-15 and 2017-18 to support local authorities to embed the special education needs and disabilities reforms as set out in the Children and Families Act 2014. In addition, we are allocating £6 billion in high needs funding in 2018-19 which local authorities can use to secure special educational provision.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","125575 ; 125577","2018-02-02T14:49:12.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833814/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833814/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833814/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-30","Special Educational Needs: Cerebral Palsy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what information his Department holds on the number of children and young people with special educational needs who have cerebral palsy.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","125572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833815","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-09","<p>As stated in the 2016-17 National Offender Management Service Annual Report, the contracting exercise “exposed that historically the costs of maintenance and services were not clearly understood by the business and consequently planning assumptions have not held true.”</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","125574","2018-02-09T12:33:48.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833815/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833815/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833815/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-30","Amey and Carillion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice,what estimate he has made of the savings accrued by the Ministry of Justice as a result of the decision to outsource Facilities Management in prisons to Amey and Carillion in 2014.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","125573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833816","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-09","<p>As stated in the 2016-17 National Offender Management Service Annual Report, the contracting exercise “exposed that historically the costs of maintenance and services were not clearly understood by the business and consequently planning assumptions have not held true.”</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","125573","2018-02-09T12:33:48.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833816/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833816/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833816/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-30","Amey and Carillion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the savings accrued to his Department were as a result of the decision to outsource Facilities Management in prisons to Amey and Carillion in each year since the start of that contract.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","125574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833817","Department for Education","false","2018-02-02","<p>The department does not collect data in this level of detail for the child or young person’s type of need.</p><p> </p><p>We collect annual data from schools and colleges on special educational needs (SEN) as part of the School Census. This data is published annually each January.</p><p> </p><p>Primary type of need is collected for those pupils with a statement of SEN or Education, Health and Care (EHC) plan. There are 12 categories of need, including physical disability. This is the highest level of detail that is collected.</p><p> </p><p>The latest figures are available in Table 8 of the National Tables on the department’s website at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/special-educational-needs-in-england-january-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/special-educational-needs-in-england-january-2017</a>.</p><p>Under the Children and Families Act 2014, local authorities are required to conduct statutory EHC needs assessments to determine whether children and young people in their area have special educational needs which require additional support or provision. Where a local authority deems that a statutory EHC plan should be issued, it is responsible for securing the special educational provision specified in the plan.</p><p>The department has provided local authorities with £252 million between 2014-15 and 2017-18 to support local authorities to embed the special education needs and disabilities reforms as set out in the Children and Families Act 2014. In addition, we are allocating £6 billion in high needs funding in 2018-19 which local authorities can use to secure special educational provision.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","125572 ; 125577","2018-02-02T14:49:12.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833817/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833817/answer",,,,