"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833960","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-07","<p>The average number of prison staff deployed on DD each month (4 week average) over the last 12 months is shown in the table below. Detached duty is one of the sensible and proportionate measures we take to ensure we run safe and decent regimes in prisons and respond appropriately to any operational issues that arise.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Month</p></td><td><p>Average number of Officers deployed on DD</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jan-17</p></td><td><p>126</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Feb-17</p></td><td><p>117</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Mar-17</p></td><td><p>105</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Apr-17</p></td><td><p>127</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>May-17</p></td><td><p>95</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jun-17</p></td><td><p>98</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jul-17</p></td><td><p>136</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Aug-17</p></td><td><p>176</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sep-17</p></td><td><p>209</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Oct-17</p></td><td><p>211</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nov-17</p></td><td><p>189</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Dec-17</p></td><td><p>198</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-02-07T15:52:28.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833960/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833960/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833960/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-30","Prison Officers: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prison staff were deployed on detached duty in each month of 2017.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","125717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833961","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-07","<p>The information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>The deployment of staff between prisons on detached duty is a regular and normal part of prison resourcing. It allows staff to be allocated from prisons with the capacity to provide them, to those where additional staffing is required. Since October 2013, national detached duty has been coordinated centrally. Detached duty is one of the sensible and proportionate measures we take to ensure we run safe and decent regimes in prisons and respond appropriately to any operational issues that arise.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-02-07T15:54:12.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833961/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833961/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833961/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-30","Prison Officers: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many days of detached duty were worked by prison staff in 2017.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","125718"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833962","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-07","<p>The information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>The current arrangements to coordinate detached duty nationally started in October 2013.</p><p> </p><p>The deployment of staff between prisons on detached duty is a regular and normal part of prison resourcing. It allows staff to be allocated from prisons with the capacity to provide them, to those where additional staffing is required. Detached duty is one of the sensible and proportionate measures we take to ensure we run safe and decent regimes in prisons and respond appropriately to any operational issues that arise.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-02-07T15:54:47.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833962/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833962/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833962/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-30","Prison Officers: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many days of detached duty were worked by prison staff in 2010.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","125719"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833964","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-07","<p>The HMCTS Reform Delivery Partner contract awarded to PwC has been published on Contracts Finder (<a href="https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Notice/20ffccdd-e93a-4e99-bc9a-9093cb983f70" target="_blank">https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Notice/20ffccdd-e93a-4e99-bc9a-9093cb983f70</a>) including the deliverables for the 6 initial work packages. However, the plans for delivery have not been published as they are considered to be commercially sensitive. The plans include details of delivery approaches and methods unique to PwC.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-02-07T14:02:14.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833964/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833964/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833964/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-30","Courts: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 26 January 2018 to Question 123660 on Courts: ICT, if he will publish the plans to deliver against the 6 initial work packages.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","125721"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833965","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-02-02","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions has received a number of written representations on the Midland Pension which is now part of the HSBC Bank (UK) Pension Schemes about its integrated pension scheme (or claw-back) policy from individuals and from Members of Parliament writing on their behalf.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2018-02-02T11:18:11.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833965/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833965/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833965/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-30","HSBC: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what reports she has received on the practice of HSBC Bank plc to deduct state deduction claw-back from its pensioners.","false","Biography information for Ian Blackford","Ross, Skye and Lochaber","Ian Blackford","125722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833966","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-07","<p>This document covers all suppliers providing facilities management services to prisons, as such there is not a Carillion specific section. This document is therefore unable to be provided on grounds of commercial sensitivity.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-02-07T15:55:29.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833966/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833966/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833966/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-30","Carillion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 25 January 2018 to Question 123441, on Prisons: Repairs and Maintenance, if he will publish the sections of the independent review referred to in that Answer which relate to Carillion.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","125723"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833967","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-07","<p>An estimated 264 Service leavers during Financial Year (FY) 2015-16 used a billable Career Transition Partnership (CTP) service and self-reported as being economically inactive for ‘other’ reasons (i.e. not in education, training or volunteering, travelling or abroad, reporting medical reasons, looking after family or retired) six months after leaving Service. Of these;</p><ul><li>34 were estimated to be Naval Service leavers</li><li>156 were estimated to be Army Service leavers</li><li>74 were estimated to be RAF Service leavers</li></ul><p> </p><p>An estimated 233 Service leavers during FY 2016-17 used a billable CTP service and self-reported as being economically inactive for ‘other’ reasons (i.e. not in education, training or volunteering, travelling or abroad, reporting medical reasons, looking after family or retired) six months after leaving Service. Of these;</p><ul><li>47 were estimated to be Naval Service leavers</li><li>136 were estimated to be Army Service leavers</li><li>50 were estimated to be RAF Service leavers</li></ul><p> </p><p>Data held on reasons for economic inactivity were not processed and compiled prior to FY 2015-16.</p><p> </p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-02-07T17:03:18.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833967/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833967/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833967/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-30","Armed Forces: Resignations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to his Department's Career Transition Partnership Annual statistics: UK Regular Service Personnel Employment 1 April 2012 to 31 March 2017 published on 25 January 2018,  how many Service leavers from (a) the Royal Navy (b) the Army (c) the RAF classed as economically inactive six months after leaving their branch of the armed forces were not in (i) in Education, training, volunteering  (ii) Travelling or abroad (iii) economically inactive due to medical reasons (iv) looking after family (v) in retirement; in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","125724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833968","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-07","<p>As a result of a proactive performance and assurance framework set up to manage public sector prisons, those identified in need of support are being placed in special measures. This is a relatively new process and the number of prisons subject to special measures has increased gradually as support processes have been developed.</p><p> </p><p>The table below shows the of prisons placed in special measures since the process commenced in 2016:</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p>NUMBER OF PRISONS IN SPECIAL MEASURE BY MONTH</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Month</p></td><td><p>Number of prisons</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>September</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>October</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>November</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>December</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>January</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>February</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>March</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>April</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>May</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>June</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>July</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>August</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>September</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>October</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>November</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>December</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018</p></td><td><p>January</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-02-07T16:01:13.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833968/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833968/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833968/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-30","Prisons: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisons have been in special measures in each month since 2010.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","125725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833969","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-07","<p>The National Careers Service Contract is held by the Education and Skills Funding Agency (ESFA) and is funded by Her Majesty’s Prison and Probation Service. The in-custody element was not cancelled: the contract comes to an end on 31 March 2018.</p><p> </p><p>In line with the commitment made in the white paper, Prison Safety and Reform, to review each national contract as it comes to an end, it was decided not to extend this contract further.</p><p> </p><p>A wide range of factors affect the likelihood of a prisoner entering employment on release. Information, advice and guidance provided by Community Rehabilitation Companies, Department of Work and Pensions Prison Work Coaches and providers of Offender Learning and Skills Services, as well as National Careers Service delivery will have a positive impact on job outcomes post-custody. The Ministry of Justice does not itself employ career advisors in prison.</p><p> </p><p>In October 2016, a Machinery of Government change transferred the budget for careers advice from the Department for Education to the Ministry of Justice. Spend prior to that period was controlled by the Department for Education. In 2016-17, £12.9m was spent on the National Careers Service in custody. Spend in 2017-18 is not yet available. The budgets for future financial years have not yet been finalised.</p><p> </p><p>We do not hold information on the number of National Careers Service advisors employed in each prison in England and Wales in each year since 2010.</p><p> </p><p>In Wales, all these matters are devolved to the Welsh Government.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","125727 ; 125728 ; 125730 ; 125733 ; 125734 ; 125735","2018-02-07T15:59:37.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833969/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833969/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/833969/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-30","National Careers Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will publish the assessment his Department has made of the effect on rehabilitation of the cancellation of the work of the National Careers Service in prisons.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","125726"
